SIMPLE: seizin
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Seizin
<hw>Sei"zin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>saisine</ets>. See <er>Seize</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Possession; possession of an estate of froehold.
It may be either in <xex>deed</xex> or in <xex>law</xex>; the former
when there is actual possession, the latter when there is a right to
such possession by construction of law. In some of the United States
<xex>seizin</xex> means merely <xex>ownership</xex>.</def>
<rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of taking possession.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The thing possessed; property.</def> <rj><au>Sir M.
Halle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Commonly spelt by writers on law
<xex>seisin</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Livery of seizin</b></col>. <fld>(Eng. Law)</fld> <cd>See
Note under <er>Livery</er>, 1.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seizing</ent>⟦br⟧
